        </div>
        <div class="stat-box">
          <div class="stat-number">60–70g</div>
          <div class="stat-label">what most men actually eat per day</div>
        </div>
        <div class="stat-box">
          <div class="stat-number">50g</div>
          <div class="stat-label">the gap between average intake and 120g</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2>The Gap Is 50g — Not 100g</h2>

      <p>
        This matters for motivation. Most men eating a typical American diet land around 60–70g of protein per day. The jump to 120g feels large until you realize it's roughly two extra servings of a high-protein food — a cup of Greek yogurt and a chicken breast, added to what you're already eating.
      </p>

      <p>
        The gap isn't massive. It's specific and closable once you can see it. That's what tracking does — not make you eat perfectly, just make the gap visible so you can act on it.
      </p>

      <div class="link-box">
        <strong>Related</strong>
        <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/hard-to-hit-protein-goal-after-40/">Why protein goals are hard to hit after 40 — and the fixes that actually work →</a>
      </div>

      <h2>Is 120g Enough for Your Bodyweight?</h2>

      <p>
        Here's where it gets personal. 120g hits differently depending on what you weigh. The science-backed threshold is 1.2g/kg of bodyweight per day. The cards below show how 120g stacks up across the range of where most men land.
      </p>

      <!-- WEIGHT GRID -->
