      <h2>Why 120g Works After 40 (The Biology in 60 Seconds)</h2>

      <p>
        After 40, your muscles become less responsive to protein — a process called <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/anabolic-resistance-after-40/">anabolic resistance</a>. What triggered muscle protein synthesis at 25 no longer works as efficiently. You need more protein per meal — and more per day — just to get the same signal your muscles got automatically when you were younger.
      </p>

      <p>
        The old RDA of 0.8g/kg was set to prevent deficiency in young adults. It was never designed for muscle maintenance in men over 40. The 1.2g/kg threshold emerged from research into exactly this problem — giving aging muscle the protein signal it needs despite reduced sensitivity.
      </p>

      <div class="pull-quote">
        <p>"120g isn't an ambitious goal for men over 40. It's the corrected baseline for what your body actually needs now."</p>
      </div>

      <h2>When Should You Aim Higher Than 120g?</h2>

      <p>
        If any of the following describes you, 120g is a solid floor — but not your ceiling:
      </p>

      <ul style="margin: 0 0 24px 24px; line-height: 2;">
        <li>You weigh over 220 lbs</li>
        <li>You lift seriously 4–5 days per week</li>
        <li>Your goal is active muscle building, not just maintenance</li>
        <li>You're in a caloric deficit and want to protect muscle mass</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        For these men, the optimizer tier — 150–180g — is worth targeting. The mechanics are the same: hit your protein number daily, spread across meals, prioritize 30g+ per sitting to overcome anabolic resistance. The number is just bigger.
      </p>

      <h2>The Real Problem Isn't the Target — It's Seeing It</h2>

      <p>
        Whether your number is 120g or 150g, the challenge is the same: most men have no idea where they stand at 2pm. You know you ate something with protein. You don't know if it was 18g or 38g. By dinner you're guessing.
      </p>

      <p>
        That's not a willpower problem. It's a visibility problem. Once you can see the number — in real time, at a glance — hitting it stops being a mystery and starts being a habit.
      </p>

