        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Is 120g of protein enough for men over 40?</h3>
          <p>For most men over 40 in the 160–210 lb range, 120g per day is a solid and well-researched target. It clears the 1.2g/kg threshold supported by current research on muscle maintenance after 40. Heavier men or serious lifters may need 140–160g or more.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>How much protein does a 180 lb man need after 40?</h3>
          <p>A 180 lb man needs roughly 98–110g of protein per day at the 1.2g/kg threshold. 120g puts him comfortably above that — which is exactly where you want to be when maintaining or building muscle after 40.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>When is 120g not enough protein after 40?</h3>
          <p>If you weigh over 220 lbs, train seriously 4–5 days a week, or are actively trying to build muscle rather than maintain it, you may need 140–180g per day. 120g becomes the floor, not the target, for heavier or more active men.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Why don't you use the 1g per pound rule?</h3>
          <p>The 1g per pound rule is gym-culture shorthand, not a research-backed standard. For men over 40 focused on muscle maintenance and healthy aging — not competitive bodybuilding — the 1.2g/kg threshold (about 0.54g/lb) is what the current science on anabolic resistance and sarcopenia supports.</p>
